reasoning:
1. Circle of Competence: I’ve spent my life in consumer products, insurance, banking and simple industrials. Alphabet (GOOG) is a complex technology and advertising business driven by algorithms and regulatory scrutiny—well outside my circle. 
2. Competitive Moat: There’s no denying Alphabet has a powerful franchise with Google Search, YouTube and the Android ecosystem. That said, network effects and data advantages in ad tech are territory I haven’t made my bed in. 
3. Management Quality: Sundar Pichai and his team are smart operators, but I’ve not studied their capital-allocation decisions the way I have with Ken Langone at Home Depot or the folks at See’s Candies. 
4. Financial Health & Consistency: With no balance sheet or earnings data in front of me, I can’t judge debt levels, return on equity or the durability of cash flow. 
5. Valuation: Intrinsic value depends on long-term cash-flow forecasts—the user’s data shows none. Without a margin of safety calculation, I’d be flying blind on price. 
6. Long-Term Prospects & Red Flags: The business is likely to endure, but it faces antitrust actions, shifting consumer privacy norms and competition from Amazon and Meta. Those are risks I don’t fully grasp. 
7. Portfolio Comparison: I’d rather put capital into businesses I understand—Coca-Cola’s syrup system, Apple’s loyal customers, BNSF’s rails—than stake it on something I can’t evaluate. 
In short, I’d pass on GOOG at present. I simply don’t know it well enough to declare a buy or sell.”
